[normal]Written evidence from the Torbay Rail Users Group (TIC 100)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Torbay Line Rail Users Group is a cross-party group who have been working for more than ten years to improve rail services to and from To
[normal]rbay for long distance, regional and local travel.  Torbay is a unitary authority of three towns, Torquay, Paignton and Brixham.  It is
[normal] the second largest conurbation
[normal] west of Bristol, 
[normal]with a resident
[normal] and increasing 
[normal] population of 135,000,  
[normal]second only to P
[normal]lym
[normal]outh and larger than Exeter.  It is one o
[normal]f
[normal] the most important tourist resorts in Britain with outstanding cultural resources.  It has
[normal] well over 
[normal]one million staying visitors and 
[normal]three
[normal] million day visitors each year.    The most important industry is tour
[normal]ism.  For a conurbation
[normal] of 
[normal] this size, the inadequacy of its rail services make it an isolated community, isolated from neighbouring towns and areas;  the 
[normal]lack
[normal] of 
[normal] many 
[normal]evening and Sunday bus services make most areas of the conurbation isolated.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]improve access to White Rock/Long Park area where residential and b
[normal]usiness accommodation is being developed and  the South Devon College and its pioneering Energy Centre are located
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Torbay’s Industries, Businesses and Services
[normal]              
[normal] 1. Tourism is Torbay’s biggest industry contributing roug
[normal]h
[normal]ly one third of the income and one third of the employment in the area.  This industry depends 
[normal]on 
[normal]good rail services.   Existing services are not adequate for the number of passengers and there are not enough direct trains.
[normal]  Passengers do not like changing trains as the results of surveys both by Passenger Focus and by
[normal] the
[normal] Torbay Line Rail 
[normal]Users Group
[normal] 
[normal](TLRUG) have shown.     Services should run daily, Mondays to Sundays, throughout the year
[normal].
[normal]  
[normal]S
[normal]hort breaks whether mid-week or at weekends are increasing and services need to 
[normal]m
[normal]ee
[normal]t
[normal] this development.
