[normal]Train timetables for services
[normal] 
[normal]between
[normal] Torbay 
[normal]and
[normal] Newton Abbot
[normal], Plymo
[normal]uth, Gunnislake, Exeter St Davids, Exeter Central, Exmouth, Crediton
[normal], 
[normal]Barnstaple and Tiverton  have been examined.  All these places, except Barnstaple, are within a 30-mile radius of Torbay and therefore within commuting distance  or  practicable for 
[normal]day
[normal] 
[normal]or evening visits – in short for
[normal] education, employment, 
[normal]business, leisure 
[normal]and a wide range of cultural and other activities
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]In practice, only visits to Newton Abbot and to some extent Exeter fall within this category.  
[normal]9.  This is not the result of a sh
[normal]ortage of trains, but of their timing, the lack of direct trains, good connections and of frequent trains in the evenings, al
[normal]though there are often more trains on summer Saturdays. 
[normal]   
[normal]Torbay
[normal] is
[normal] isolated from 
[normal]other areas
[normal] and they are isolated from Torbay
[normal], a
[normal] serious disadvantage for Torbay’s tourist trade.
[normal]10.
[normal]  
[normal]All trains from Paignton, the end of the line in Torbay, must pass through Newton Abbot, whatever their further destination.  Of the 30 trains that depart from Paignton on Mondays to Fridays, two leave
[normal] at 15 minutes past the hour, eight leave at 15
[normal] 
[normal]minutes past plus or minus five minutes; another four leave plus or minus ten minutes – which could involve a wait of 20 minutes.  The gaps between trains are very erratic: eight are of 50 to 59 minutes, and 
[normal]another six of 40 to 49 minutes.  These big gaps are unpredictable.  The timetable is so erratic that would-be passengers are effectively discouraged from using the trains.
[normal]              
[normal]11
[normal].  Long distance trains 
[normal]to
[normal] London Paddington
[normal] and to Manchester, 
[normal]the Midlands and North of England are slotted erratically in between the erratic local trains.  
[normal]P
[normal]assengers to 
[normal]or from 
[normal]such destinations 
[normal]are likely to check train times in advance.
[normal]12
[normal].  Trains 
[normal]between
[normal] Torbay 
[normal]and
[normal] Plymouth are wanted and needed.  Sixty four p
[normal]er cent of respondents to a
[normal] small survey or poll run by
[normal] TLRUG gave this as their most desired improvement.  There are no direct trains between Torbay and Plymouth and connections are few.
[normal]  A
[normal]ny journey between Torbay and Plymouth 
[normal]takes 15 minutes between Pa
[normal]ignton and  Newton Abbot and 40 minutes between  Newton Abbot and Plymouth
[normal].  
[normal]T
[normal]he timetable
[normal]s
[normal] for Mondays to Fridays
[normal] show that ‘
[normal]c
[normal]onnections’  between -3 or -1 minute (the onward train departs 3 minutes or one minute before the train from Torbay arrive
[normal]s
[normal])  or
[normal] one minute (catch-it-if-you-run-fast)  and a wait of up to 44 minutes.  
[normal]Nine
[normal] connections involve waits of 
[normal]10 minutes or less
[normal] and eight waits of 1
[normal]1
[normal] - 2
[normal]0
[normal] minutes
[normal];  waits of 20 minutes can add 40 minutes to a return journey, a considerable addition to a 
[normal]daily commute
[normal].  All the rest are longer.   Woe betide  the commuter who takes the 8.23 from Paignton arriving at Newton Abbot at 8.39; the next train to Plymouth arrives at 9.57, a wait of  1 hour and 18 minutes, the more galling because the previous train
[normal] leaves Newton Abbot at 8.35, four minutes earlier.   There are other gaps in the timetable
[normal] when there are no sensible connections.  Connections between Plymouth and Torbay
[normal] 
[normal]and on Saturdays and Sundays show similar patterns and are of  very limited value t
[normal]o those making either regular or occasional journeys.
