[normal]28.  
[normal]Access to and from other parts of the county are diffic
[normal]ult and normally depend on making connections at Exeter, Plymouth
[normal], or another town.    Some services do not run every day, for example from a village to a town for a shopping expedition, so of no use to someone wishing to visit a village or a friend or rel
[normal]ative there.  Some services run only one to four trips daily,
[normal] excluding evenings and Sundays,
[normal] so making possible difficulties in making return trips for whatever purpose, whether work, education, for hospital visits 
[normal]or similar reasons or
[normal] 
[normal] visit
[normal]s to
[normal] friends
[normal] or relatives.  These difficulties arise both for those coming to Torbay and for those going from Torbay.
[normal]  It can be impossible to make a daytime return visit, still more to make an evening visit. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Resilience
[normal]              
[normal]29.  
[normal]For
[normal] resilience, not only is the Teign Valley line or an equivalent required, but also the re-establishment of the former rout
[normal]e via Okehampton – Tavistock – Plymouth.  A first stage would be the re-establishment of a regular daily service between Exeter and Ok
[normal]ehampton, particularly useful as a result of the recent closure of  several businesses and consequent increase in unemployment in Okehampton.  The line from Tavistock to Bere Alston and Plymouth is already 
[normal]well advanced
[normal].  This leaves only the gap between O
[normal]kehampton and Tavistock to be re-established.  
[normal]              
[normal]30.  In view of the increasing number of rail passengers and of older people who are less likely to drive, and of the need to reduce emissions from vehicles 
[normal]to meet the Government’s targets for climate chang
[normal]e,
[normal]  provision should be made by regulation, or if necessary by legislation, to safeguard 
[normal]the track of 
[normal]former rail lines, so that they remain avail
[normal]able 
[normal]to be brought back into use.
